  "prompt": "What are some free alternatives to Aha.io?",
  "response": "Aha.io is a popular product management and roadmapping tool, but there are several free alternatives that you might consider. Here are some of them:\n\n1. **Trello**: A versatile project management tool that uses boards, lists, and cards to organize tasks and projects. While it has paid features, the free version is quite robust for basic project tracking.\n\n2. **Asana**: Another popular project management tool that offers a free tier. It allows teams to track tasks and projects, set deadlines, and collaborate.\n\n3. **ClickUp**: Offers a wide range of project management and productivity features. The free plan includes many functionalities that could fit small teams.\n\n4. **Notion**: A highly flexible tool that can be used for project management, notes, databases, and more. The free version has sufficient features for individual users or small teams.\n\n5. **Roadmunk**: While it primarily caters to product roadmapping, it offers a free trial that can be good for short-term projects.\n\n6. **Airtable**: A spreadsheet-database hybrid that is highly customizable for project management, product tracking, and more. The free tier includes essential features for small teams.\n\n7. **Milestones**: A lightweight project management tool that helps teams keep track of project deadlines and progress. The free tier is simple and does not require much setup.\n\n8. **Productboard**: Offers a free plan tailored for startups that need to prioritize features based on customer feedback. While it has limited functionalities compared to paid versions, it may serve basic needs.\n\n9. **GitHub Projects**: If your team is engaged in software development, GitHub Projects can serve as a lightweight project management tool integrated with your code repository.\n\n10. **Google Sheets**: While not a specialized tool, Google Sheets can be adapted for project management and roadmapping. Many templates are available to help set it up for this purpose.\n\nThese tools cater to different needs, so you might want to explore a few to find the one that best fits your workflow.",
